Date: Sat, 11 Sep 1999 08:03:43 -0700
From: Willaim K. Reisen <arbo@lightspeed.net>

There are several aspects of _Culex pipiens_ biology that should be
considered at
this juncture in time and in the future.
1. Based upon previous studies on this mosquito [Eldridge 1968. Am. J.
Trop. Med. Hyg. 17: 133; Spielman & Wong 1973 J. Med Entomol. 10: 319;
Spielman & Wong 1973, Ann. Entomol. Soc. Am. 66: 905, most newly emerging
females should be or will soon be entering reproductive diapause at this
time based on photoperiod conditions. This should bring the epidemic to a
natural end, at least for this winter. I would expect, however, a
considerable time lag until all the cases are recognized.
2. During warm "Indian summer" conditions, females destined for diapause
reportedly exhibit gonotrophic dissociation; i.e., take small blood meals,
but do not develop eggs. These females can become infected with SLE and
potentially serve as an overwintering mechanism for this virus [see
reference below.
3. If there is a large population present, I would expect successful
overwintering in both above and below ground structures that remain cold. I
think that a mosquito/SLE surveillance program should be established this
winter and careful monitoring of infection in components of the enzootic
cycle next summer [should be done. This could prevent the need for
emergency adult control that seems to be currently on-going.
--
Bill Reisen
University of California, Davis
e-mail: arbo@lightspeed.net
[In a previous comment I indicated that it was Joel Dalrymple et al. who
has isolated SLE virus from overwintering adult mosquitoes in Maryland.
Doug Watts let us know that it was Charlie Bailey who was the senior author
on that seminal paper; Doug Watts was a co-author. Here is the reference:
Bailey CL, Eldridge BF, Hayes DE, Watts DM, Tammariello RF, and Dalrymple
JM. (1978) Isolation of St. Louis encephalitis virus from overwintering
_Culex pipiens_ mosquitoes. Science. 199:1346-1349. Doug also was involved
in the original research showing that La Crosse bunyavirus was
transovarially transmitted, so he ought to know. I am grateful for the
correction. Led me to reread some neat stuff. - Mod.CHC
*********
[2
Date: Sat, 11 Sep 1999 10:02:12 -0500
From: Blaine Hollinger <blaineh@melnick.mvir.bcm.tmc.edu>

In response to the comments by Lucas Terracina, the epidemic of SLE in
Corpus Christi, Texas in the summer of 1966 traced the distribution of
cases to the combined effects of an unusual distribution of vector mosquito
breeding sites in storm sewers in the upper socioeconomic districts and a
higher degree of residual immunity in the residents of the lower
socioeconomic areas. This is important to recognize since treatment of
open sources is relatively easy, but leaves these other possible sites as
potential sources of infected mosquitoes. In that outbreak, the infection
rate in mosquitoes was 1:151 before aerial spraying. After spraying, the
mosquito counts in the established resting sites were reduced to 5-10% of
their previous levels for about 5 days. No additional isolations of SLE
virus were made from more than 4600 _Culex quinquefasciatus_ collected over
the next 2 months. In addition, once it was established that large numbers
of mosquitoes were present deep within the drains, an insecticidal fog
machine was used to force a fog of 5% malathion and diesel fuel for great
distances within the drains, traveling as much as 0.8 km in one occasion.
Methodology is described in the paper [referenced below. Human cases are
the last in the chain of events and the peak number of confirmed cases may
not occur for 4-6 weeks.
Reference:
Williams, Hollinger, Metzger, Hopkins and Chamberlain. Amer J Epid
1975;102:16
--
F. Blaine Hollinger, M.D.
Professor of Medicine, Virology and Epidemiology
Director, Eugene B. Casey Hepatitis & HIV Research Center
and Diagnostic Laboratory
e-mail: blaineh@melnick.mvir.bcm.tmc.edu

[I believe Bill and Blaine are indicating the epidemic peak in NY City may
not occur for some weeks yet. I agree and others with whom I have spoken
agree that this is the likely scenario. - Mod.CHC
