[3
Date: 12 September 1999
From: C.H. Calisher <calisher@usa.healthnet.org>

Earlier today I spoke with Dr. William C. Reeves, now retired from the
University of California at Berkeley, but, as far as I and many others are
concerned, still the expert in SLE virus epidemiology. In response to my
question as to when the last outbreak of SLE occurred in New York, he
didn't recall there having been any. That probably means there haven't
been any. In response to my question regarding whether the recent weather
conditions in New York were usual or unusual for SLE epidemics, he pointed
out that 1933, the year SLE virus was recognized from an epidemic in St.
Louis , Missouri, had been the driest on record in that city.
Conversations with others, not exactly off the record but not attributable
to them, led me to believe that (a) Based on inapparent:apparent ratios
documented in previous outbreaks and epidemics, there may very well have
been many more cases of SLE virus infection (not necessarily St. Louis
encephalitis, although some of these may also have been unrecognized),
including mild cases and asymptomatic infections, in NY City. (b) The zero
based budgeting used by NY City might discourage investing in studies of or
surveillance for a disease that has not occurred in the area, (c) Bob
Novak's and Paul Grimstad's comments about catch basins and sewers as a
source of adult mosquitoes could be right on with respect to NY City. As
best I can tell, the infrastructure below the streets of New York is
antiquated and basically uncharted. The Department of Health would have to
consult with various other city departments, various utilities (gas,
electric, telephone), the subway folks), etc.; a nightmare. (d) Nearby
Nassau County cut its vector control budget and, as had NY City, been
involved mainly with pest control. Some folks might not know a pest
mosquito from a potential vector. (e) The current thinking is that
extensive aerial and ground applications of malathion will do the job for
now. Obviously, it is too late to consider source reduction or larviciding
on a large scale, so the short-term goal is to reduce the adult mosquito
population. It is these mosquitoes that are carrying the virus and by
reducing these populations around NY City (as, we trust, is being done
elsewhere in the area) at least interrupt the mosquito-bird virus
amplification cycle and thereby prevent further human infections/illnesses.
Good weather will be needed to conduct successful spraying operations.
Finally, I have a question for our readers: What is the likelihood that a
single bird or a few birds, infected with SLE virus (from where?) decided
to nest only in Queens County and that this is not a problem of the entire
NY City area, which to me includes Connecticut, Westchester County (NY),
and New Jersey? If the cases occurring this year are the only ones that
occur, then the entire metropolitan NY area has dodged a bullet. As Bill
Reisen has said, indications are that additional studies will be required
next year -- but this one is not yet over.
--
C.H. Calisher
Moderator, Virus Diseases
ProMED
e-mail: calisher@usa.healthnet.org
